<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-654-638  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 654 638.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  July 16 1990 v4 n27 p28(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The future of Ada.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Poos, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The service branches are now using the Department of Defense's(DOD) ADA programming language for financial and payrollfunctions, logistics systems, and personnel records and reportingsystems.andP;  Previously, ADA application was limited to those onembedded computers guiding ballistic missiles and automatingaircraft, among others.andP;  ADA's structure and maintainability makeit useful for large-scale programs.andP;  The DOD's ADA 9X revisionproject improves the real-time speed of the language to make itmore popular with users.andP;  Budget cuts stifle the growth predictedfor ADA by reducing the number of ADA-based contracts, but thelanguage is expected to gradually become more popular.andP;  NASAchooses ADA for a space station project, while the FAA adopts ADAfor its Advanced Automation System and its Office AutomationTechnology and Services contracts.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ADAOutlookProgramming LanguagesFuture of ComputingUnited States. Department of DefenseBudgeting.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Types of planned Ada projects as of 1989. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>